## Work discipline

- Every substantial change should trace to `[spec, task, notebook, issue, or workstream]`.
- Keep the project's durable artifacts current as part of the work.
- Do not let code move while specs, milestones, status, or analysis records go stale.
- Recon before action: inspect the real file, live state, or caller before changing behavior.
- Use existing helpers and runners as black boxes first; read their source only when you must customize or debug.
- Merge, don't clobber: when updating this file, configs, or steering docs, preserve existing structure.
- Do not take shortcuts to satisfy tests, checklists, or milestone optics.
- Do not ask subagents to take shortcuts either.
- Before ending substantial work, update the session handoff below.

## Work efficiency

- Run independent tool calls in parallel; avoid serial waits that do not share data.
- Delegate isolated research, mechanical batches, or large searches to subagents; bring back summaries, not transcripts.
- Use a two-agent split (planner/executor or coder/reviewer) when the task cleanly separates roles.
- Verify subagent claims against files, tests, or live state before acting on them.
- Never fabricate output in place of running a tool. If a tool call would answer the question, run it.

## Verification standards

- Do not add empty tests or symbolic assertions.
- Use verification that exercises real behavior.
- Match the surface to the risk:
  - unit for local logic
  - integration for boundaries
  - end-to-end for user workflows
- When a UI or browser flow exists, use real E2E or integration tooling such as Agent Browser or Playwright.
- Inspect real rendered/runtime state before automating dynamic flows; discover selectors and boundaries from reality, not assumption.
- Do not hardcode around the failure, weaken the test, or skip the real path just to get green results.
- Record honest verification status in `[status doc or tracker]`.

